  "markdown": "\n# Let's Step It Up A Little - Breakdown Part 4\n\nOK, we've reached the last few pieces of this conversation which take place after the drinks are ready:\n\n- **Barista**\n> Seo duit! Is é seo an latte.\n> Sho gwich! Iss ay sho un LAH-teh.\n> Here you are! This is the latte.\n\n- **Customer**\n> Go raibh míle maith agat.\n> Guh rev MEE-leh mah ah-gut.\n> Thanks a million.\n\n- **Barista**\n> Fadhb ar bith.\n> Fowb er bih.\n> No problem.\n\nWhen the drinks are ready, the barista hands them over.\n\n`Seo duit` - \"Here you are.\"\nYou’ve already seen this one.\n\n`Is é seo an latte` is a clear way of identifying something - \"This is the latte.\"\n\nYou might also hear:\n- `Agus is é seo an tae glas.` – \"And this is the green tea.\"\n- `Is é seo do chaife.` – \"This is your coffee.\"\n\nYou don’t need to break this structure apart, just recognise it as a useful way of pointing something out clearly.\n\nNext, the customer says:\n\n`Go raibh míle maith agat.`\n\nYou’ve already seen `Go raibh maith agat.`  Adding `míle` (a thousand) turns it into \"Thanks a thousand\", or more naturally, \"Thanks a million.\"\n\nAnd finally:\n`Fadhb ar bith.`\n\nYou’ve seen `ar bith` before. It adds that familiar \"at all\" feeling, so this phrase means “no problem at all.”\n\nYou might also hear:\n- `Ná habair é.` – \"Don’t mention it.\"\n- `Tá fáilte romhat.` – \"You’re welcome.\" (Can also be abbreviated to `Fáilte`)\n\nAnd that brings the conversation to a natural close.",
